# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chest-mechanical-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/chest-mechanical-engineering] A **valve chest** (often called a **steam chest**) is a chamber or housing in a steam engine that contains valves controlling the admission, distribution, or regulation of steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/chest-mechanical-engineering] In reciprocating steam engines, the valve chest is typically mounted adjacent to or above the cylinder and encloses the valve gear that distributes steam during operation.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/chest-mechanical-engineering] In steam-turbine installations, the term may also refer to a separate chamber or casing that houses turbine stop valves or control valves regulating steam flow into the turbine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/chest-mechanical-engineering] It is normally closed by a removable cover or lid sealed with a gasket to allow inspection and maintenance of the valve components.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A **gasket** is a mechanical seal which fills the space between two or more mating surfaces, generally to prevent leakage from or into the joined objects while under compression.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] It is a deformable material that is used to create a static seal and maintain that seal under various operating conditions in a mechanical assembly.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Gaskets allow for "less-than-perfect" mating surfaces on machine parts where they can fill irregularities.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Gaskets are commonly produced by cutting from sheet materials.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Given the potential cost and safety implications of faulty or leaking gaskets, it is critical that the correct gasket material is selected to fit the needs of the application.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Gaskets for specific applications, such as high pressure steam systems, may contain asbestos.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] However, due to health hazards associated with asbestos exposure, non-asbestos gasket materials are used when practical.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] It is usually desirable that the gasket be made from a material that is to some degree yielding such that it is able to deform and tightly fill the space it is designed for, including any slight irregularities.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Some types of gaskets require a sealant be applied directly to the gasket surface to function properly.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Some (piping) gaskets are made entirely of metal and rely on a seating surface to accomplish the seal; the metal's own spring characteristics are utilized (up to but not passing σy, the material's yield strength).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] This is typical of some "ring joints" (RTJ) or some other metal gasket systems.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] These joints are known as R-con and E-con compressive type joints.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Some gaskets are dispensed and cured in place.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] These materials are called formed-in-place gaskets.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Gaskets are normally made from a flat material, a sheet such as paper, rubber, silicone, metal, cork, felt, neoprene, nitrile rubber, fiberglass, polytetrafluoroethylene (otherwise known as PTFE or Teflon) or a plastic polymer (such as polychlorotrifluoroethylene).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] One of the more desirable properties of an effective gasket in industrial applications for compressed fiber gasket material is the ability to withstand high compressive loads.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Most industrial gasket applications involve bolts exerting compression well into the 14 MPa (2000 psi) range or higher.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Generally speaking, there are several truisms that allow for better gasket performance.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] One of the more tried and tested is: "The more compressive load exerted on the gasket, the longer it will last".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] There are several ways to measure a gasket material's ability to withstand compressive loading.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The "hot compression test" is probably the most accepted of these tests.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Most manufacturers of gasket materials will provide or publish the results of these tests.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Gaskets can be produced by punching the required shape out of a sheet of flat, thin material, resulting in a *sheet gaskets*.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Sheet gasket are fast and cheap to produce, and can be produced from a variety of materials, among them fibrous materials and matted graphite (and in the past - compressed asbestos).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] These gaskets can fill various different chemical requirements based on the inertness of the material used.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Non-asbestos gasket sheet is durable, of multiple materials, and thick in nature.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Material examples are mineral, carbon or synthetic rubbers such as EPDM, Nitrile, Neoprene, Natural, SBR Insertion - each of which have unique properties suitable for different applications.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Applications using sheet gaskets involve acids, corrosive chemicals, steam or mild caustics.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Flexibility and good recovery prevent breakage during installation of a sheet gasket.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The idea behind solid material is to use metals which cannot be punched out of sheets but are still cheap to produce.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] These gaskets generally have a much higher level of quality control than sheet gaskets and generally can withstand much higher temperatures and pressures.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The key downside is that a solid metal must be greatly compressed in order to become flush with the flange head and prevent leakage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The material choice is more difficult; because metals are primarily used, process contamination and oxidation are risks.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] An additional downside is that the metal used must be softer than the flange — in order to ensure that the flange does not warp and thereby prevent sealing with future gaskets.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Even so, these gaskets have found a niche in industry.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Spiral-wound gaskets, invented by Flexitallic in 1912 comprise a mix of metallic and filler material.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Generally, the gasket has a metal (normally carbon rich or stainless steel) wound outwards in a circular spiral (other shapes are possible) with the filler material (generally a flexible graphite) wound in the same manner but starting from the opposing side.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] This results in alternating layers of filler and metal.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The filler material in these gaskets acts as the sealing element, with the metal providing structural support.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] These gaskets have proven to be reliable in most applications, but do not allow for lower sealing loads as the metal element needs to be compressed in order to provide an effective seal.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The constant seating stress gasket consists of two components; a solid carrier ring of a suitable material, such as stainless steel, and two sealing elements of some compressible material installed within two opposing channels, one channel on either side of the carrier ring.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The sealing elements are typically made from a material (expanded graphite, expanded polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE), vermiculite, etc.) suitable to the process fluid and application.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Constant seating stress gaskets derive their name from the fact that the carrier ring profile takes flange rotation (deflection under bolt preload) into consideration.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] With all other conventional gaskets, as the flange fasteners are tightened, the flange deflects radially under load, resulting in the greatest gasket compression, and highest gasket stress, at the outer gasket edge.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Thus, the gasket is immune to common gasket failure modes that include creep relaxation, high system vibration, or system thermal cycles.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Double-jacketed gaskets are another combination of filler material and metallic materials.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] In this application, a tube with ends that resemble a "C" is made of the metal with an additional piece made to fit inside of the "C" making the tube thickest at the meeting points.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The filler is pumped between the shell and piece.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] When in use, the compressed gasket has a larger amount of metal at the two tips where contact is made (due to the shell/piece interaction) and these two places bear the burden of sealing the process.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Since all that is needed is a shell and piece, these gaskets can be made from almost any material that can be made into a sheet and a filler can then be inserted.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Kammprofile gaskets (sometimes spelled "Camprofile" due to their design resembling the profile of a camshaft, which is a rotating component in internal combustion engines.) are used in many older seals since they have both a flexible nature and reliable performance.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Kammprofiles work by having a solid grooved core with a soft covering layer.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] This arrangement allows for very high compression without damage to the gasket and an extremely tight seal.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Kammprofile gaskets has a high capital cost for most applications but this is countered by long life and increased reliability.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Kammprofile gaskets allow for low sealing loads, as a seal is formed as soon as the soft covering is fully compressed.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] As the metal core provides a solid support, they have an incredibly wide range of allowable gasket stress.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Fishbone gaskets are direct replacements for kammprofile and spiralwound gaskets.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] They are fully CNC machine manufactured from similar materials but the design of the gaskets has eliminated inherent short comings.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Fishbone gaskets do not unwind in storage or in the plant.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The rounded edges do not cause flange damage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The added "Stop Step" prevents the fishbone gaskets from being over compressed/crushed, often caused by hot torque techniques on plant start up.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The bones of the gasket remain ductile and adjust to thermal cycling and system pressure spikes, resulting in a durable and reliable flange seal that out performs all other gaskets of this nature significantly.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A **flange gasket** is a type of gasket made to fit between two sections of pipe that are flared to provide higher surface area.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Flange gaskets come in a variety of sizes and are categorized by their inside diameter and their outside diameter.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] There are many standards in gasket for flanges of pipes.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Soft gasket is a term that refers to a gasket that is cut from a soft (flexible) sheet material and can easily conform to surface irregularities even when the bolt load is low.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Soft gaskets are used in applications such as heat exchangers, compressors, bonnet valve and pipe flanges.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Annular Seal (RTJ Seal) is a high integrity, high temperature, high pressure seal for applications in the oil industry, oilfield drilling, pressure vessel connections, pipes, valves and more.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] The movement of the ring packing (RTJ) can be described as an irregular flow in the groove of the deformed sealing flange due to the axial compressive load.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Colored seal (RTJ seal) has a small load area, which leads to a large surface pressure between the sealing surface and the groove, the maintenance properties are poor and not suitable for reuse.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Uneven pressure can be caused by a variety of factors.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] First is the human factor: asymmetric application of the bolt preload, this can cause uneven pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Theoretically when the flanges are pressed, the sealing surfaces are absolutely parallel, in practice however, the centerline of a pipeline cannot be absolutely concentric, and tightening the bolts on the flange moment makes the flange a discontinuity.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] With asymmetric connections, the seal surfaces will be more or less deformed and the pressure reduced, the running load, prone to leakage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Third, the density of bolt arrangement has an obvious impact on the pressure distribution, the closer the bolts, the more uniform the pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Due to vibration, temperature changes, and other factors such as spiral wound gasket stress relaxation, the bolt tension will gradually decrease, resulting in loss of torque, causing a leak.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] In general longer bolts and smaller diameters of bolt are better at preventing the loss of torque.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A long thin bolt is an effective way to prevent torque loss.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Heating for a certain period of time to stretch the bolt, and then maintaining a given torque, is very effective in preventing the loss of torque.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] When the gasket is thinner and smaller there will be a greater loss of torque.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] In addition, prevent strong vibration of the machine and the pipe itself, and isolate them from adjacent equipment vibration.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Impacts on the sealing surface are not meaningless.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] Not impacting the tightened bolts can prevent the loss of torque.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] It is important to make the sealing finish properly otherwise it will cause leakage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A surface that is too smooth can allow your gasket material to blow out under pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A surface that is not machined flat can provide leak paths.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A good rule of thumb is a machined surface to 32RMS.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] This insures the surface is flat, but with enough surface finish to bite into the gasket under compression.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] With metal core coated gaskets, both sides of the core are covered with a flexible, malleable sealant.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] There are reinforced metal seals in the pressure class up to 300.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/gasket] A strong metal core prevents pressure seals and a soft core ensures exceptional sealing.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A **steam engine** is a heat engine that performs mechanical work using steam as its working fluid.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The steam engine uses the force produced by steam pressure to push a piston back and forth inside a cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This pushing force can be transformed by a connecting rod and crank into rotational force for work.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The term “steam engine” is normally applied to reciprocating engines, although some authorities have also referred to the steam turbine and devices such as Hero's aeolipile as “steam engines”.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The essential feature of steam engines is that they are external combustion engines, where the working fluid is separated from the combustion products.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The ideal thermodynamic cycle used to analyze this process is called the Rankine cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In general usage, the term “steam engine” can refer to either complete steam plants (including boilers etc.), such as railway steam locomotives and portable engines, or may refer to the piston or turbine machinery alone, as in the beam engine and stationary steam engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam-driven devices such as the aeolipile were known in the first century AD, and few other uses were recorded in the 16th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1606 Jerónimo de Ayanz y Beaumont patented his invention of the first steam-powered water pump for draining mines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Thomas Savery is considered the inventor of the first commercially used steam powered device, a steam pump that used steam pressure operating directly on the water.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The first commercially successful engine that could transmit continuous power to a machine was developed in 1712 by Thomas Newcomen.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1764, James Watt made a critical improvement by removing spent steam to a separate vessel for condensation, greatly improving the amount of work obtained per unit of fuel consumed.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] By the 19th century, stationary steam engines powered the factories of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam engines led to the replacement of sailing ships by paddle steamers, and steam locomotives operated on the railways.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Reciprocating piston type steam engines were the dominant source of power until the early 20th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The efficiency of stationary steam engines increased dramatically until about 1922.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The highest Rankine Cycle Efficiency of 91% and combined thermal efficiency of 31% was demonstrated and published in 1921 and 1928.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Advances in the design of electric motors and internal combustion engines resulted in the gradual replacement of steam engines in commercial usage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam turbines replaced reciprocating engines in power generation, due to lower cost, higher operating speed, and higher efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Note that small scale steam turbines are much less efficient than large ones.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As of 2023, large reciprocating piston steam engines are still being manufactured in Germany.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] One recorded rudimentary steam-powered engine was the aeolipile described by Hero of Alexandria, a Hellenistic mathematician and engineer in Roman Egypt during the first century AD.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the following centuries, the few steam-powered engines known were, like the aeolipile, essentially experimental devices used by inventors to demonstrate the properties of steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A rudimentary steam turbine device was described by Taqi al-Din in Ottoman Egypt in 1551 and by Giovanni Branca in Italy in 1629.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1601, Giambattista della Porta, described an apparatus by which the pressure of steam might be made to raise a column of water.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Spanish inventor Jerónimo de Ayanz received patents in 1606 for 50 steam-powered inventions, including a water pump for draining inundated mines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] By 1615, Salomon de Caus developed a solar-powered atmospheric engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Frenchman Denis Papin did some useful work on the steam digester in 1679, and first used a piston to raise weights in 1690.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The first commercial steam-powered device was a water pump, developed in 1698 by Thomas Savery.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It used condensing steam to create a vacuum which raised water from below and then used steam pressure to raise it higher.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Small engines were effective though larger models were problematic.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] They had a very limited lift height and were prone to boiler explosions.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Savery's engine was used in mines, pumping stations and supplying water to water wheels powering textile machinery.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] One advantage of Savery's engine was its low cost.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Bento de Moura Portugal introduced an improvement of Savery's construction “to render it capable of working itself”, as described by John Smeaton in the Philosophical Transactions published in 1751.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It continued to be manufactured until the late 18th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] At least one engine was still known to be operating in 1820.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The first commercially successful engine that could transmit continuous power to a machine was the atmospheric engine (or "fire engine"), invented by Thomas Newcomen around 1712.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It improved on Savery's steam pump, using a piston as proposed by Papin.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Newcomen's engine was relatively inefficient, and mostly used for pumping water.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It worked by creating a partial vacuum by condensing steam under a piston within a cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It was employed for draining mine workings at depths originally impractical using traditional means, and for providing reusable water for driving waterwheels at factories sited away from a suitable “head”.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Water that passed over the wheel was pumped up into a storage reservoir above the wheel.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1780 James Pickard patented the use of a flywheel and crankshaft to provide rotative motion from an improved Newcomen engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1720, Jacob Leupold described a two-cylinder high-pressure steam engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The invention was published in his major work "Theatri Machinarum Hydraulicarum".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The engine used two heavy pistons to provide motion to a water pump.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Each piston was raised by the steam pressure and returned to its original position by gravity.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The two pistons shared a common four-way rotary valve connected directly to a steam boiler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The next major step occurred when James Watt developed (1763–1775) an improved version of Newcomen's engine, with a separate condenser.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Boulton and Watt's early engines used half as much coal as John Smeaton's improved version of Newcomen's.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Newcomen's and Watt's early engines were "atmospheric".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] They were powered by air pressure pushing a piston into the partial vacuum generated by condensing steam, instead of the pressure of expanding steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The engine [cylinders had to be large because the only usable force acting on them was atmospheric pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Watt developed his engine further, modifying it to provide a rotary motion suitable for driving machinery.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This enabled factories to be sited away from rivers, and accelerated the pace of the Industrial Revolution.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The meaning of high pressure, together with an actual value above ambient, depends on the era in which the term was used.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] For early use of the term Van Reimsdijk refers to steam being at a sufficiently high pressure that it could be exhausted to atmosphere without reliance on a vacuum to enable it to perform useful work.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Ewing states that Watt's condensing engines were known, at the time, as low pressure compared to high pressure, non-condensing engines of the same period.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Watt's patent prevented others from making high pressure and compound engines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Shortly after Watt's patent expired in 1800, Richard Trevithick and, separately, Oliver Evans in 1801 introduced engines using high-pressure steam; Trevithick obtained his high-pressure engine patent in 1802, and Evans had made several working models before then.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These were much more powerful for a given cylinder size than previous engines and could be made small enough for transport applications.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Thereafter, technological developments and improvements in manufacturing techniques (partly brought about by the adoption of the steam engine as a power source) resulted in the design of more efficient engines that could be smaller, faster, or more powerful, depending on the intended application.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Cornish engine was developed by Trevithick and others in the 1810s.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It was a compound cycle engine that used high-pressure steam expansively, then condensed the low-pressure steam, making it relatively efficient.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Cornish engine had irregular motion and torque through the cycle, limiting it mainly to pumping.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Cornish engines were used in mines and for water supply until the late 19th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Early builders of stationary steam engines considered that horizontal cylinders would be subject to excessive wear.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Their engines were therefore arranged with the piston axis in vertical position.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In time the horizontal arrangement became more popular, allowing compact, but powerful engines to be fitted in smaller spaces.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The acme of the horizontal engine was the Corliss steam engine, patented in 1849, which was a four-valve counter flow engine with separate steam admission and exhaust valves and automatic variable steam cutoff.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] When Corliss was given the Rumford Medal, the committee said that "no one invention since Watt's time has so enhanced the efficiency of the steam engine".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In addition to using 30% less steam, it provided more uniform speed due to variable steam cut off, making it well suited to manufacturing, especially cotton spinning.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The first experimental road-going steam-powered vehicles were built in the late 18th century, but it was not until after Richard Trevithick had developed the use of high-pressure steam, around 1800, that mobile steam engines became a practical proposition.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The first half of the 19th century saw great progress in steam vehicle design, and by the 1850s it was becoming viable to produce them on a commercial basis.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This progress was dampened by legislation which limited or prohibited the use of steam-powered vehicles on roads.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Improvements in vehicle technology continued from the 1860s to the 1920s.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam road vehicles were used for many applications.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the 20th century, the rapid development of internal combustion engine technology led to the demise of the steam engine as a source of propulsion of vehicles on a commercial basis, with relatively few remaining in use beyond the Second World War.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Many of these vehicles were acquired by enthusiasts for preservation, and numerous examples are still in existence.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the 1960s, the air pollution problems in California gave rise to a brief period of interest in developing and studying steam-powered vehicles as a possible means of reducing the pollution.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Apart from interest by steam enthusiasts, the occasional replica vehicle, and experimental technology, no steam vehicles are in production at present.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Near the end of the 19th century, compound engines came into widespread use.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Compound engines exhausted steam into successively larger cylinders to accommodate the higher volumes at reduced pressures, giving improved efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These stages were called expansions, with double- and triple-expansion engines being common, especially in shipping where efficiency was important to reduce the weight of coal carried.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As the development of steam engines progressed through the 18th century, various attempts were made to apply them to road and railway use.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1784, William Murdoch, a Scottish inventor, built a model steam road locomotive.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] An early working model of a steam rail locomotive was designed and constructed by steamboat pioneer John Fitch in the United States probably during the 1780s or 1790s.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] His steam locomotive used interior bladed wheels guided by rails or tracks.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The design incorporated a number of important innovations that included using high-pressure steam which reduced the weight of the engine and increased its efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Trevithick visited the Newcastle area later in 1804 and the colliery railways in north-east England became the leading centre for experimentation and development of steam locomotives.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Trevithick continued his own experiments using a trio of locomotives, concluding with the Catch Me Who Can in 1808.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Only four years later, the successful twin-cylinder locomotive *Salamanca* by Matthew Murray was used by the edge railed rack and pinion Middleton Railway.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In 1825 George Stephenson built the *Locomotion* for the Stockton and Darlington Railway.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This was the first public steam railway in the world and then in 1829, he built *The Rocket* which was entered in and won the Rainhill Trials.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Liverpool and Manchester Railway opened in 1830 making exclusive use of steam power for both passenger and freight trains.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam locomotives continued to be manufactured until the late twentieth century in places such as China and the former East Germany (where the DR Class 52.80 was produced).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The final major evolution of the steam engine design was the use of steam turbines starting in the late part of the 19th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam turbines are generally more efficient than reciprocating piston type steam engines (for outputs above several hundred horsepower), have fewer moving parts, and provide rotary power directly instead of through a connecting rod system or similar means.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam turbines virtually replaced reciprocating engines in electricity generating stations early in the 20th century, where their efficiency, higher speed appropriate to generator service, and smooth rotation were advantages.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Today most electric power is provided by steam turbines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the United States, 90% of the electric power is produced in this way using a variety of heat sources.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam turbines were extensively applied for propulsion of large ships throughout most of the 20th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Although the reciprocating steam engine is no longer in widespread commercial use, various companies are exploring or exploiting the potential of the engine as an alternative to internal combustion engines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The world's smallest working "steam engine" was revealed in 2011.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The micro-scale engine was developed by two German scientists at the University of Stuttgart.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It operates on the principle of a Stirling engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] There are two fundamental components of a steam plant: the boiler or steam generator, and the "motor unit", referred to itself as a "steam engine".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Stationary steam engines in fixed buildings may have the boiler and engine in separate buildings some distance apart.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] For portable or mobile use, such as steam locomotives, the two are mounted together.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The widely used reciprocating engine typically consisted of a cast-iron cylinder, piston, connecting rod and beam or a crank and flywheel, and miscellaneous linkages.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam was alternately supplied and exhausted by one or more valves.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Speed control was either automatic, using a governor, or by a manual valve.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The cylinder casting contained steam supply and exhaust ports.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Engines equipped with a condenser are a separate type than those that exhaust to the atmosphere.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] When coal is used, a chain or screw stoking mechanism and its drive engine or motor may be included to move the fuel from a supply bin (bunker) to the firebox.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The heat required for boiling the water and raising the temperature of the steam can be derived from various sources, most commonly from burning combustible materials with an appropriate supply of air in a closed space (e.g., combustion chamber, firebox, furnace).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the case of model or toy steam engines and a few full scale cases, the heat source can be an electric heating element.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Boilers are pressure vessels that contain water to be boiled, and features that transfer the heat to the water as effectively as possible.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Water is passed through tubes surrounded by hot gas.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Hot gas is passed through tubes immersed in water, the same water also circulates in a water jacket surrounding the firebox and, in high-output locomotive boilers, also passes through tubes in the firebox itself (thermic syphons and security circulators).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Fire-tube boilers were the main type used for early high-pressure steam (typical steam locomotive practice), but they were to a large extent displaced by more economical water tube boilers in the late 19th century for marine propulsion and large stationary applications.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Many boilers raise the temperature of the steam after it has left that part of the boiler where it is in contact with the water.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Known as superheating, it turns wet steam into superheated steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It avoids the steam condensing in the engine cylinders, and gives a significantly higher efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These "motor units" are often called 'steam engines' in their own right.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Engines using compressed air or other gases differ from steam engines only in details that depend on the nature of the gas although compressed air has been used in steam engines without change.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As with all heat engines, the majority of primary energy must be emitted as waste heat at relatively low temperature.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The simplest cold sink is to vent the steam to the environment.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This is often used on steam locomotives to avoid the weight and bulk of condensers.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Some of the released steam is vented up the chimney so as to increase the draw on the fire, which greatly increases engine power, but reduces efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Sometimes the waste heat from the engine is useful itself, and in those cases, very high overall efficiency can be obtained.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam engines in stationary power plants use surface condensers as a cold sink.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The condensers are cooled by water flow from oceans, rivers, lakes, and often by cooling towers which evaporate water to provide cooling energy removal.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The resulting condensed hot water (*condensate*), is then pumped back up to pressure and sent back to the boiler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A dry-type cooling tower is similar to an automobile radiator and is used in locations where water is costly.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Waste heat can also be ejected by evaporative (wet) cooling towers, which use a secondary external water circuit that evaporates some of flow to the air.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] River boats initially used a jet condenser in which cold water from the river is injected into the exhaust steam from the engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] While this was also applied for sea-going vessels, generally after only a few days of operation the boiler would become coated with deposited salt, reducing performance and increasing the risk of a boiler explosion.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Starting about 1834, the use of surface condensers on ships eliminated fouling of the boilers, and improved engine efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Evaporated water cannot be used for subsequent purposes (other than rain somewhere), whereas river water can be re-used.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In all cases, the steam plant boiler feed water, which must be kept pure, is kept separate from the cooling water or air.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Most steam boilers have a means to supply water whilst at pressure, so that they may be run continuously.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Utility and industrial boilers commonly use multi-stage centrifugal pumps; however, other types are used.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Another means of supplying lower-pressure (typically about 5 to 10 atm (73 to 147 psi)) boiler feed water is an injector, which uses a steam jet usually supplied from the boiler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Injectors became popular in the 1850s but are no longer widely used, except in applications such as steam locomotives.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It is the pressurization of the water that circulates through the steam boiler that allows the water to be raised to temperatures well above 100 °C (212 °F) boiling point of water at one atmospheric pressure, and by that means to increase the efficiency of the steam cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] For safety reasons, nearly all steam engines are equipped with mechanisms to monitor the boiler, such as a pressure gauge and a sight glass to monitor the water level.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Many engines, stationary and mobile, are also fitted with a governor to regulate the speed of the engine without the need for human interference.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The most useful instrument for analyzing the performance of steam engines is the steam engine indicator.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Early versions were in use by 1851, but the most successful indicator was developed for the high speed engine inventor and manufacturer Charles Porter by Charles Richard and exhibited at London Exhibition in 1862.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The steam engine indicator traces on paper the pressure in the cylinder throughout the cycle, which can be used to spot various problems and calculate developed horsepower.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It was routinely used by engineers, mechanics and insurance inspectors.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The engine indicator can also be used on internal combustion engines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] See image of indicator diagram below (in *Types of motor units* section).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one on the equipment of a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed, because it would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped only with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The governor was improved over time and coupled with variable steam cut off, good speed control in response to changes in load was attainable near the end of the 19th century.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In a simple engine, or "single expansion engine", the charge of steam passes through the entire expansion process in an individual cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A simple engine may have one or more individual cylinders.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It is then exhausted directly into the atmosphere or into a condenser.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As steam expands in passing through a high-pressure engine, its temperature drops because no heat is being added to the system; this is known as adiabatic expansion and results in steam entering the cylinder at high temperature and leaving at lower temperature.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This causes a cycle of heating and cooling of the cylinder with every stroke, which is a source of inefficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The dominant efficiency loss in reciprocating steam engines is cylinder condensation and re-evaporation.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The steam cylinder and adjacent metal parts/ports operate at a temperature about halfway between the steam admission saturation temperature and the saturation temperature corresponding to the exhaust pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As high-pressure steam is admitted into the working cylinder, much of the high-temperature steam is condensed as water droplets onto the metal surfaces, significantly reducing the steam available for expansive work.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] When the expanding steam reaches low pressure (especially during the exhaust stroke), the previously deposited water droplets that had just been formed within the cylinder/ports now boil away (re-evaporation) and this steam does no further work in the cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] There are practical limits on the expansion ratio of a steam engine cylinder, as increasing cylinder surface area tends to exacerbate the cylinder condensation and re-evaporation issues.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This negates the theoretical advantages associated with a high ratio of expansion in an individual cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A method to lessen the magnitude of energy loss to a very long cylinder was invented in 1804 by British engineer Arthur Woolf, who patented his *Woolf high-pressure **compound engine*** in 1805.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the compound engine, high-pressure steam from the boiler expands in a **high-pressure (HP) cylinder** and then enters one or more subsequent **lower-pressure (LP) cylinders**.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The complete expansion of the steam now occurs across multiple cylinders, with the overall temperature drop within each cylinder reduced considerably.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] By expanding the steam in steps with smaller temperature range (within each cylinder) the condensation and re-evaporation efficiency issue (described above) is reduced.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This reduces the magnitude of cylinder heating and cooling, increasing the efficiency of the engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] By staging the expansion in multiple cylinders, variations of torque can be reduced.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] To derive equal work from lower-pressure cylinder requires a larger cylinder volume as this steam occupies a greater volume.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Therefore, the bore, and in rare cases the stroke, are increased in low-pressure cylinders, resulting in larger cylinders.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Double-expansion (usually known as **compound**) engines expanded the steam in two stages.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The pairs may be duplicated or the work of the large low-pressure cylinder can be split with one high-pressure cylinder exhausting into two low pressure cylinders, giving a three-cylinder layout where cylinder and piston diameter are about the same, making the reciprocating masses easier to balance.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] With two-cylinder compounds used in railway work, the pistons are connected to the cranks as with a two-cylinder simple at 90° out of phase with each other (*quartered*).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] When the double-expansion group is duplicated, producing a four-cylinder compound, the individual pistons within the group are usually balanced at 180°, the groups being set at 90° to each other.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In one case (the first type of Vauclain compound), the pistons worked in the same phase driving a common crosshead and crank, again set at 90° as for a two-cylinder engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] With the three-cylinder compound arrangement, the LP cranks were either set at 90° with the HP one at 135° to the other two, or in some cases, all three cranks were set at 120°.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The adoption of compounding was common for industrial units, for road engines and almost universal for marine engines after 1880; it was not universally popular in railway locomotives where it was often perceived as complicated.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This is partly due to the harsh railway operating environment and limited space afforded by the loading gauge (particularly in Britain, where compounding was never common and not employed after 1930).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] However, although never in the majority, it was popular in many other countries.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It is a logical extension of the compound engine (described above) to split the expansion into yet more stages to increase efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The result is the **multiple-expansion engine**.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Such engines use either three or four expansion stages and are known as *triple-* and *quadruple-expansion engines* respectively.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These engines use a series of cylinders of progressively increasing diameter.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These cylinders are designed to divide the work into equal shares for each expansion stage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] As with the double-expansion engine, if space is at a premium, then two smaller cylinders may be used for the low-pressure stage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Multiple-expansion engines typically had the cylinders arranged inline, but various other formations were used.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the late 19th century, the Yarrow-Schlick-Tweedy balancing "system" was used on some marine triple-expansion engines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Y-S-T engines divided the low-pressure expansion stages between two cylinders, one at each end of the engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This allowed the crankshaft to be better balanced, resulting in a smoother, faster-responding engine which ran with less vibration.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This made the four-cylinder triple-expansion engine popular with large passenger liners (such as the *Olympic* class), but this was ultimately replaced by the virtually vibration-free turbine engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It is noted, however, that triple-expansion reciprocating steam engines were used to drive the World War II Liberty ships, by far the largest number of identical ships ever built.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Over 2700 ships were built, in the United States, from a British original design.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The image in this section shows an animation of a triple-expansion engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The steam travels through the engine from left to right.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The valve chest for each of the cylinders is to the left of the corresponding cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Land-based steam engines could exhaust their steam to atmosphere, as feed water was usually readily available.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Prior to and during World War I, the expansion engine dominated marine applications, where high vessel speed was not essential.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It was, however, superseded by the British invention steam turbine where speed was required, for instance in warships, such as the dreadnought battleships, and ocean liners.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] HMS *Dreadnought* of 1905 was the first major warship to replace the proven technology of the reciprocating engine with the then-novel steam turbine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In most reciprocating piston engines, the steam reverses its direction of flow at each stroke (counterflow), entering and exhausting from the same end of the cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The complete engine cycle occupies one rotation of the crank and two piston strokes; the cycle also comprises four *events* – admission, expansion, exhaust, compression.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These events are controlled by valves often working inside a *steam chest* adjacent to the cylinder; the valves distribute the steam by opening and closing steam *ports* communicating with the cylinder end(s) and are driven by valve gear, of which there are many types.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The simplest valve gears give events of fixed length during the engine cycle and often make the engine rotate in only one direction.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Many however have a reversing mechanism which additionally can provide means for saving steam as speed and momentum are gained by gradually "shortening the cutoff" or rather, shortening the admission event; this in turn proportionately lengthens the expansion period.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the 1840s and 1850s, there were attempts to overcome this problem by means of various patent valve gears with a separate, variable cutoff expansion valve riding on the back of the main slide valve; the latter usually had fixed or limited cutoff.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The combined setup gave a fair approximation of the ideal events, at the expense of increased friction and wear, and the mechanism tended to be complicated.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The usual compromise solution has been to provide *lap* by lengthening rubbing surfaces of the valve in such a way as to overlap the port on the admission side, with the effect that the exhaust side remains open for a longer period after cut-off on the admission side has occurred.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This expedient has since been generally considered satisfactory for most purposes and makes possible the use of the simpler Stephenson, Joy, and Walschaerts motions.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Before the exhaust phase is quite complete, the exhaust side of the valve closes, shutting a portion of the exhaust steam inside the cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The aim of the uniflow is to remedy this defect and improve efficiency by providing an additional port uncovered by the piston at the end of each stroke making the steam flow only in one direction.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] By this means, the simple-expansion uniflow engine gives efficiency equivalent to that of classic compound systems with the added advantage of superior part-load performance, and comparable efficiency to turbines for smaller engines below one thousand horsepower.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] However, the thermal expansion gradient uniflow engines produce along the cylinder wall gives practical difficulties..
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A steam turbine consists of one or more *rotors* (rotating discs) mounted on a drive shaft, alternating with a series of *stators* (static discs) fixed to the turbine casing.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The rotors have a propeller-like arrangement of blades at the outer edge.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam acts upon these blades, producing rotary motion.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The stator consists of a similar, but fixed, series of blades that serve to redirect the steam flow onto the next rotor stage.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A steam turbine often exhausts into a surface condenser that provides a vacuum.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The stages of a steam turbine are typically arranged to extract the maximum potential work from a specific velocity and pressure of steam, giving rise to a series of variably sized high- and low-pressure stages.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Turbines are only efficient if they rotate at relatively high speed, therefore they are usually connected to reduction gearing to drive lower speed applications, such as a ship's propeller.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the vast majority of large electric generating stations, turbines are directly connected to generators with no reduction gearing.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Typical speeds are 3600 revolutions per minute (RPM) in the United States with 60 Hertz power, and 3000 RPM in Europe and other countries with 50 Hertz electric power systems.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In nuclear power applications, due to enormous size, the turbines typically run at half these speeds, 1800 RPM and 1500 RPM.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A turbine rotor is also only capable of providing power when rotating in one direction.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Therefore, a reversing stage or gearbox is usually required where power is required in the opposite direction.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam turbines provide direct rotational force and therefore do not require a linkage mechanism to convert reciprocating to rotary motion.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Thus, they produce smoother rotational forces on the output shaft.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] This contributes to a lower maintenance requirement and less wear on the machinery they power than a comparable reciprocating engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In electricity production, the high speed of turbine rotation matches well with the speed of modern electric generators, which are typically direct connected to their driving turbines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In recent decades, reciprocating Diesel engines, and gas turbines, have almost entirely supplanted steam propulsion for marine applications.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Virtually all nuclear power plants generate electricity by heating water to provide steam that drives a turbine connected to an electrical generator.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Nuclear-powered ships and submarines either use a steam turbine directly for main propulsion, with generators providing auxiliary power, or else employ turbo-electric transmission, where the steam drives a turbo generator set with propulsion provided by electric motors.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] A limited number of steam turbine railroad locomotives were manufactured.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Some non-condensing direct-drive locomotives did meet with some success for long haul freight operations in Sweden and for express passenger work in Britain, but were not repeated.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Elsewhere, notably in the United States, more advanced designs with electric transmission were built experimentally, but not reproduced.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It was found that steam turbines were not ideally suited to the railroad environment and these locomotives failed to oust the classic reciprocating steam unit in the way that modern diesel and electric traction has done.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] An oscillating cylinder steam engine is a variant of the simple expansion steam engine which does not require valves to direct steam into and out of the cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Instead of valves, the entire cylinder rocks, or oscillates, such that one or more holes in the cylinder line up with holes in a fixed port face or in the pivot mounting (trunnion).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] These engines are mainly used in toys and models because of their simplicity, but have also been used in full-size working engines, mainly on ships where their compactness is valued.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It is possible to use a mechanism based on a pistonless rotary engine such as the Wankel engine in place of the cylinders and valve gear of a conventional reciprocating steam engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Many such engines have been designed, from the time of James Watt to the present day, but relatively few were actually built and even fewer went into quantity production; see link at bottom of article for more details.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The major problem is the difficulty of sealing the rotors to make them steam-tight in the face of wear and thermal expansion; the resulting leakage made them very inefficient.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Lack of expansive working, or any means of control of the cutoff, is also a serious problem with many such designs.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] By the 1840s, it was clear that the concept had inherent problems and rotary engines were treated with some derision in the technical press.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] However, the arrival of electricity on the scene, and the obvious advantages of driving a dynamo directly from a high-speed engine, led to something of a revival in interest in the 1880s and 1890s, and a few designs had some limited success..
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Of the few designs that were manufactured in quantity, those of the Hult Brothers Rotary Steam Engine Company of Stockholm, Sweden, and the spherical engine of Beauchamp Tower are notable.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Tower's engines were used by the Great Eastern Railway to drive lighting dynamos on their locomotives, and by the Admiralty for driving dynamos on board the ships of the Royal Navy.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] They were eventually replaced in these niche applications by steam turbines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The aeolipile represents the use of steam by the rocket-reaction principle, although not for direct propulsion.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In more modern times there has been limited use of steam for rocketry – particularly for rocket cars.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam rocketry works by filling a pressure vessel with hot water at high pressure and opening a valve leading to a suitable nozzle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The drop in pressure immediately boils some of the water and the steam leaves through a nozzle, creating a propulsive force.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Ferdinand Verbiest's carriage was powered by an aeolipile in 1679.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam engines possess boilers and other components that are pressure vessels that contain a great deal of potential energy.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam escapes and boiler explosions (typically BLEVEs) can and have in the past caused great loss of life.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] While variations in standards may exist in different countries, stringent legal, testing, training, care with manufacture, operation and certification is applied to ensure safety.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Steam engines frequently possess two independent mechanisms for ensuring that the pressure in the boiler does not go too high; one may be adjusted by the user, the second is typically designed as an ultimate fail-safe.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Such safety valves traditionally used a simple lever to restrain a plug valve in the top of a boiler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] One end of the lever carried a weight or spring that restrained the valve against steam pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Early valves could be adjusted by engine drivers, leading to many accidents when a driver fastened the valve down to allow greater steam pressure and more power from the engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The more recent type of safety valve uses an adjustable spring-loaded valve, which is locked such that operators may not tamper with its adjustment unless a seal is illegally broken.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Lead fusible plugs may be present in the crown of the boiler's firebox.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] If the water level drops, such that the temperature of the firebox crown increases significantly, the lead melts and the steam escapes, warning the operators, who may then manually suppress the fire.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Except in the smallest of boilers the steam escape has little effect on dampening the fire.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The plugs are also too small in area to lower steam pressure significantly, depressurizing the boiler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] If they were any larger, the volume of escaping steam would itself endanger the crew.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Rankine cycle is the fundamental thermodynamic underpinning of the steam engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The cycle is an arrangement of components as is typically used for simple power production, and uses the phase change of water (boiling water producing steam, condensing exhaust steam, producing liquid water) to provide a practical heat/power conversion system.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The heat is supplied externally to a closed loop with some of the heat added being converted to work and the waste heat being removed in a condenser.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Rankine cycle is used in virtually all steam power production applications.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In the 1990s, Rankine steam cycles generated about 90% of all electric power used throughout the world, including virtually all solar, biomass, coal, and nuclear power plants.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] It is named after William John Macquorn Rankine, a Scottish polymath.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The Rankine cycle is sometimes referred to as a practical Carnot cycle because, when an efficient turbine is used, the TS diagram begins to resemble the Carnot cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The main difference is that heat addition (in the boiler) and rejection (in the condenser) are isobaric (constant pressure) processes in the Rankine cycle and isothermal (constant temperature) processes in the theoretical Carnot cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] In this cycle, a pump is used to pressurize the working fluid which is received from the condenser as a liquid not as a gas.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Pumping the working fluid in liquid form during the cycle requires a small fraction of the energy to transport it compared to the energy needed to compress the working fluid in gaseous form in a compressor (as in the Carnot cycle).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The cycle of a reciprocating steam engine differs from that of turbines because of condensation and re-evaporation occurring in the cylinder or in the steam inlet passages.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The working fluid in a Rankine cycle can operate as a closed loop system, where the working fluid is recycled continuously, or may be an "open loop" system, where the exhaust steam is directly released to the atmosphere, and a separate source of water feeding the boiler is supplied.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Normally water is the fluid of choice due to its favourable properties, such as non-toxic and unreactive chemistry, abundance, low cost, and its thermodynamic properties.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Mercury is the working fluid in the mercury vapor turbine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Low boiling hydrocarbons can be used in a binary cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The steam engine contributed much to the development of thermodynamic theory; however, the only applications of scientific theory that influenced the steam engine were the original concepts of harnessing the power of steam and atmospheric pressure and knowledge of properties of heat and steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The experimental measurements made by Watt on a model steam engine led to the development of the separate condenser.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Watt independently discovered latent heat, which was confirmed by the original discoverer Joseph Black, who also advised Watt on experimental procedures.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Watt was also aware of the change in the boiling point of water with pressure.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] Otherwise, the improvements to the engine itself were more mechanical in nature.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p01] The thermodynamic concepts of the Rankine cycle did give engineers the understanding needed to calculate efficiency which aided the development of modern high-pressure and -temperature boilers and the steam turbine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The efficiency of an engine cycle can be calculated by dividing the energy output of mechanical work that the engine produces by the energy put into the engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The historical measure of a steam engine's energy efficiency was its "duty".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The concept of duty was first introduced by Watt in order to illustrate how much more efficient his engines were over the earlier Newcomen designs.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Duty is the number of foot-pounds of work delivered by burning one bushel (94 lb (43 kg)) of coal.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The best examples of Newcomen designs had a duty of about 7 million, but most were closer to 5 million.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Watt's original low-pressure designs were able to deliver duty as high as 25 million, but averaged about 17.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] This was a three-fold improvement over the average Newcomen design.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Early Watt engines equipped with high-pressure steam improved this to 65 million.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The Carnot cycle, a theoretical ideal thermodynamic cycle, sets the limit of a steam engine's efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Carnot cycle describes a system of two thermal reservoirs with heat transferred between them.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] In a steam engine part of the heat transferred is converted into mechanical work.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The greater the difference in temperature between the two reservoirs, the more efficient the engine.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] One way of increasing the difference is by using superheated steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The efficiency of a Rankine cycle is usually limited by the working fluid.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] This gives a theoretical Carnot efficiency of about 64% compared with an actual efficiency of 42% for a modern coal-fired power station.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] This low turbine entry temperature (compared with a gas turbine) is why the Rankine cycle is often used as a bottoming cycle in combined-cycle gas turbine power stations.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] One principal advantage the Rankine cycle holds over others is that during the compression stage relatively little work is required to drive the pump, the working fluid being in its liquid phase at this point.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] By condensing the fluid, the work required by the pump consumes only 1% to 3% of the turbine (or reciprocating engine) power and contributes to a much higher efficiency for a real cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] The benefit of this is lost somewhat due to the lower heat addition temperature.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Gas turbines, for instance, have turbine entry temperatures approaching 1,500 °C (2,730 °F; 1,770 K).
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Nonetheless, the efficiencies of actual large steam cycles and large modern simple cycle gas turbines are fairly well matched.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] In practice, a reciprocating steam engine cycle exhausting the steam to atmosphere will typically have an efficiency (including the boiler) in the range of 1–10%.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] However, with the addition of a condenser, Corliss valves, multiple expansion, and high steam pressure/temperature, it may be greatly improved.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] Historically into the range of 10–20%, and very rarely slightly higher.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] A modern, large electrical power station (producing several hundred megawatts of electrical output) with steam reheat, economizer etc. will achieve efficiency in the mid 40% range, with the most efficient units approaching 50% thermal efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/steam-engine-p02] It is also possible to capture the waste heat using cogeneration in which the waste heat is used for heating a lower boiling point working fluid or as a heat source for district heating via saturated low-pressure steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The **valve gear** of a steam engine is the mechanism that operates the inlet and exhaust valves to admit steam into the cylinder and allow exhaust steam to escape, respectively, at the correct points in the cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] It is sometimes referred to as the "motion".
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] In the simple case, this can be a relatively simple task as in the internal combustion engine in which the valves always open and close at the same points.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The point at which steam stops being admitted to the cylinder is known as the *cutoff*, and the optimal position for this varies depending on the work being done and the tradeoff desired between power and efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Steam engines are fitted with regulators (throttles in US parlance) to vary the restriction on steam flow, but controlling the power via the cutoff setting is generally preferable since it makes for more efficient use of boiler steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] A further benefit may be obtained by admitting the steam to the cylinder slightly before front or back dead centre.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] This advanced admission (also known as *lead steam*) assists in cushioning the inertia of the motion at high speed.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] In the internal combustion engine, this task is performed by cams on a camshaft driving poppet valves, but this arrangement is not commonly used with steam engines, partly because achieving variable engine timing using cams is complicated.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Instead, a system of eccentrics, cranks and levers is generally used to control a D slide valve or piston valve from the motion.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Generally, two simple harmonic motions with different fixed phase angles are added in varying proportions to provide an output motion that is variable in phase and amplitude.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] A variety of such mechanisms have been devised over the years, with varying success.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Both slide and piston valves have the limitation that intake and exhaust events are fixed in relation to each other and cannot be independently optimised.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Lap is provided on steam edges of the valve, so that although the valve stroke reduces as cutoff is advanced, the valve is always fully opened to exhaust.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] However, as cutoff is shortened, the exhaust events also advance.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The exhaust release point occurs earlier in the power stroke and compression earlier in the exhaust stroke.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Early release wastes some energy in the steam, and early closure also wastes energy in compressing an otherwise unnecessarily large quantity of steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] These inefficiencies drove the widespread experimentation in poppet valve gears for locomotives.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Intake and exhaust poppet valves could be moved and controlled independently of each other, allowing for better control of the cycle.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] In the end, not a great number of locomotives were fitted with poppet valves, but they were common in steam cars and lorries, for example virtually all Sentinel lorries, locomotives and railcars used poppet valves.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] A very late British design, the SR Leader class, used sleeve valves adapted from internal combustion engines, but this class was not a success.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] In stationary steam engines, traction engines and marine engine practice, the shortcomings of valves and valve gears were among the factors that lead to compound expansion.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] In stationary engines trip valves were also extensively used.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Valve gear was a fertile field of invention, with probably several hundred variations devised over the years.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] However, only a small number of these saw any widespread use.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] They can be divided into those that drove the standard reciprocating valves (whether piston valves or slide valves), those used with poppet valves, and stationary engine trip gears used with semi-rotary Corliss valves or drop valves.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] One component of the motion comes from a crank or eccentric.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The other component comes from a separate source, usually the crosshead.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Two eccentrics joined by a curved or straight link.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] A simple arrangement which works well at low speed.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] At high speed, a Walschaerts-type gear is said to give better steam distribution and higher efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Both components of the motion come from a single crank or eccentric.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] A problem with this arrangement (when applied to locomotives) is that one of the components of the motion is affected by the rise and fall of the locomotive on its springs.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] This probably explains why radial gears were largely superseded by Walschaerts-type gears in railway practice but continued to be used in traction and marine engines.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] These enable a 3-cylinder or 4-cylinder locomotive to be built with only two sets of valve gear.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The best known is Gresley conjugated valve gear, used on 3-cylinder locomotives.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Walschaerts gear is usually used for the two outside cylinders.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Two levers connected to the outside cylinder valve rods drive the valve for the inside cylinder.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Harold Holcroft devised a different method for conjugating valve gear by linking the middle cylinder to the combination lever assembly of an outside cylinder, creating the Holcroft valve gear derivative.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] On a 4-cylinder locomotive the arrangement is simpler.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The valve gear may be inside or outside and only short rocking-shafts are needed to link the valves on the inside and outside cylinders.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Large stationary engines often used an advanced form of valve gear developed by George Henry Corliss, usually called Corliss valve gear.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] This gear used separate valves for inlet and exhaust so that the inlet cut-off could be controlled precisely.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] The use of separate valves and port passages for steam admission and exhaust significantly also reduced losses associated with cylinder condensation and re-evaporation.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] These features resulted in much improved efficiency.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] A locomotive's direction of travel and cut-off are set from the cab by using a reversing lever or screw reverser actuating a rod reaching to the valve gear proper.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] Some larger steam engines employ a power reverse, which is a servo mechanism, usually powered by steam.
[src:chest-mechanical-engineering/valve-gear] This makes control of the reversing gear easier for the driver.
